r> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(12/18/01 1:47:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=117.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Is it cowardly to use a bow?</span><hr size=1> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2>I am interested in hearing opinions on the RP use of bows as a paladin.  I have seen it argued that using a bow i.e. engaging an enemy from afar is not paladinlike.<br><br>For purposes of this poll, assume that, as in real life, a foe may be slain from one, well-placed arrow.<br><br>The Japanese refused to allow guns into their country until late into the 1800s and here is their reasoning.  It takes more of a man to stand toe-to-toe with a foe than to hide behind a tree and kill him without being seen.<br><br>So what do you, the honored and noble Paladins of Norrath think about this issue?<br><br>Ulric Pentalus<br>50th Paladin of Marr<br>Saryrn</FONT><FORM method=post action="http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathfrm9.processVote?topicID=117.topic"><table border=0 cellpadding=3 cellspacing=0 width="55%"><tbody><tr><td><input type="radio" name="choice" value="1"><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2>Yes, its cowardly.  I would never use a bow.</FONT></td></tr><tr><td><input type="radio" name="choice" value="2"><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2>No, it is completely legitimate for a paladin to use a bow.</FONT></td></tr></tbody></table><P><input type=submit value="Vote"><a HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathfrm9.showMessage?topicID=117.topic&pollResults=on><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Show results</FONT></A> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ucylria.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cylria</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(12/27/01 10:49:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=117.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Is it cowardly to use a bow?</span><hr size=1> I'd like to comment on this, because it’s kind of a pet peeve of mine.<br><br>Back when AD&amp;D was in its 1st edition, someone at TSR got it in his mind that attacking at range was less than honorable, so Paladins couldn't use bows. This was changed long before EQ came out, but somehow the ideal got implemented into EQ.<br><br>One thing you should know is that Paladins are the warriors and main line of defense for their temple. A general who didn't see the importance of bowmen would find himself defeated. The backbone of the medieval English army was its longbowmen, who weren't simple soldiers quickly trained to use a bow. To become a longbowman required training that started in childhood, and usually they came from the ranks of nobles and skilled craftsmen who could afford such for their sons.<br><br>As another example, Robin Hood was in the crusades long before he was an outlaw. Cavaliers are the basis for Paladins, and Robin only became a woodsman when he became an outlaw. It could easily be argued that he was a Paladin and not a Ranger. In either case he was a crusader and a noble when he learned to use a bow.<br><br>Yes it is true about early Japan and firearms, but remember the art of the bow has long been part of Japanese culture and warfare. It was the invention of the crossbow, and then gunpowder that took ranged combat out of the hands of highly trained men and put it in the hands of common soldiers.<br><br>Sorry about the long rant, but I came into EQ a little before Paladins could use bows, and I’m still disappointed in our incredibly low skill cap, despite historical inaccuracy.<br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ulordulric.showPublicProfile?language=EN>LordUlric</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(12/27/01 11:44:01 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=117.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Is it cowardly to use a bow?</span><hr size=1> I think you are a bit mislead about the origin of Knights and the nobility of the bow...<br><br>The nobility really never used bows.  If you think about the battle of Crecy, the French knights, when they entered the battlefield, ignored the English longbowman completely and charged the English Knights.  The French felt it dishonoroable to fight &quot;lowly&quot; longbowman.  However, the English Longbowman decimated the French Knights.  <br><br>Effectiveness of bows aside, why did the French Knights fail to engage the Longbowmen?  Because it was, in their eyes, their job was to engage the English Knights in single combat.<br><br>Ulric Pentalus<br>51st Cavalier of Marr<br>Saryrn <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ucylria.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cylria</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(12/27/01 1:38:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=117.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Is it cowardly to use a bow?</span><hr size=1> I agree Ulric. In fact it was that battle that peeked my interest in the English longbow. The French did ignore the longbowmen and paid the price for it. I see Paladins as the military branch of the church, as such a church's generals would be drawn from paladins. Any military leader who ignores the need for bowmen in battle wouldn't last very long.<br><br>I also wanted to point out that bowmen were not common soldiers given a bow and told to shoot it. To use a bow effectively they had to be highly trained (more training than your average soldier, they were the elite troops).<br><br>Target shooting as a sport isn't something that would be done by commoners (well not serfs anyhow), and traditionally bow hunting was more of a sport then a means of survival in Europe, once again a practice by those of means.<br><br>The same argument against bows could also be applied to pikemen (and Calvary), were the idea is to engage your opponent at a distance that is to your advantage.<br><br>I really think Paladins would include archery amongst games of skill like jousting and sword fighting. I also think a young noble knight, riding through the forest, would have more practice shooting at moving targets, than the more cunning ranger who’d sneak up on the unsuspecting animal.<br><br>And how does the need for bows translate into a magical world like EQ were you enemies could have scores of wizards blasting at your troops, and terrible necromancers infecting them with vile diseases. Charging into battle in Norrath could have even more dire consequences.<br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uphatis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Phatis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(12/30/01 10:49:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=117.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Is it cowardly to use a bow?</span><hr size=1> Use yo stunz to pull <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCO